ation.&quot; <br><br>Tala has studied fusion energy both here in Finland and at the world's largest fusion energy test-bed at the Joint European Torus (JET), situated at the Culham Science Centre near Oxford. <br>    The experimental device has already been harnessed to produce 16MW of peak fusion power - although it should be added that it requires 20MW of input power to do this, and is thus using more energy than it generates. By comparison, a single reactor at the Loviisa nuclear facility produces around 500MW. <br>    In the tokamak (from a contraction of the Russian words: &quot;toroidalnaya&quot;, &quot;kamera&quot;, and &quot;magnitnaya&quot;, meaning &quot;toroidal chamber-magnetic&quot;) fusion reactor, the ionised hydrogen raw material is held in a toroidal configuration, rather like a car tyre or a doughnut, where the walls are made of a material capable of withstanding very high temperatures. <br><br>Under very high temperatures and pressures, the atomic nuclei inside the chamber collide and fuse, accompanied by the release of large amounts of heat energy. The principle behind a fusion reactor is that the heat generated could be passed to water or another coolant fluid that circulates in a blanket surrounding the reactor core. The heated water would turn a turbine to generate electricity. <br>    Fusion power has long been a glittering prize in the minds of scientists - harnessing an almost limitless supply of energy of the kind that powers the stars. The vast temperatures involved have, however, thus far defied all attempts to produce a commercial solution. <br><br>**************************************************<br><br>Sounds similar to other predictions 50 years ago that predicted fusion was only 50 years away. LOL. <p><br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace"><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/website/images/title/title_03.jpg"> </a></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=